VI'm a pediatrician and an anesthesiologist,
p4
aVso I put children to sleep for a living.
p5
aV(Laughter)
p6
aVAnd I'm an academic, so I put audiences to sleep for free.
p7
aV(Laughter)
p8
aVBut what I actually mostly do
p9
aVis I manage the pain management service
p10
aVat the Packard Children's Hospital up at Stanford in Palo Alto.
p11
aVAnd it's from the experience
p12
aVfrom about 20 or 25 years of doing that
p13
aVthat I want to bring to you the message this morning,
p14
aVthat pain is a disease.
p15
aa(lp16
VNow most of the time,
p17
aVyou think of pain as a symptom of a disease,
p18
aVand that's true most of the time.
p19
aVIt's the symptom of a tumor or an infection
p20
aVor an inflammation or an operation.
p21
aVBut about 10 percent of the time,
p22
aVafter the patient has recovered from one of those events,
p23
aVpain persists.
p24
aVIt persists for months
p25
aVand oftentimes for years,
p26
aVand when that happens,
p27
aVit is its own disease.
p28
aVAnd before I tell you about how it is that we think that happens
p29
aVand what we can do about it,
p30
aVI want to show you how it feels for my patients.
p31
aVSo imagine, if you will,
p32
aVthat I'm stroking your arm with this feather,
p33
aVas I'm stroking my arm right now.
p34
aVNow, I want you to imagine
p35
aVthat I'm stroking it with this.
p36
aVPlease keep your seat.
p37
aV(Laughter)
p38
aVA very different feeling.
p39
aVNow what does it have to do with chronic pain?
p40
aVImagine, if you will, these two ideas together.
p41
aVImagine what your life would be like
p42
aVif I were to stroke it with this feather,
p43
aVbut your brain was telling you
p44
aVthat this is what you are feeling \u2014
p45
aVand that is the experience of my patients with chronic pain.
