aa(lp86
VHow can the nervous system get this so wrong?
p87
aVHow can the nervous system
p88
aVmisinterpret an innocent sensation
p89
aVlike the touch of a hand
p90
aVand turn it into the malevolent sensation
p91
aVof the touch of the flame?
p92
aVWell you probably imagine that the nervous system in the body
p93
aVis hardwired like your house.
p94
aVIn your house, wires run in the wall,
p95
aVfrom the light switch to a junction box in the ceiling
p96
aVand from the junction box to the light bulb.
p97
aVAnd when you turn the switch on, the light goes on.
p98
aVAnd when you turn the switch off, the light goes off.
p99
aVSo people imagine the nervous system is just like that.
p100
aVIf you hit your thumb with a hammer,
p101
aVthese wires in your arm \u2014 that, of course, we call nerves \u2014
p102
aVtransmit the information into the junction box in the spinal cord
p103
aVwhere new wires, new nerves,
p104
aVtake the information up to the brain
p105
aVwhere you become consciously aware that your thumb is now hurt.
p106
aa(lp107
VBut the situation, of course, in the human body
p108
aVis far more complicated than that.
p109
aVInstead of it being the case
p110
aVthat that junction box in the spinal cord
p111
aVis just simple where one nerve connects with the next nerve
p112
aVby releasing these little brown packets
p113
aVof chemical information called neurotransmitters
p114
aVin a linear one-on-one fashion,
p115
aVin fact, what happens
p116
aVis the neurotransmitters spill out in three dimensions \u2014
p117
aVlaterally, vertically, up and down in the spinal cord \u2014
p118
aVand they start interacting
p119
aVwith other adjacent cells.
p120
aVThese cells, called glial cells,
p121
aVwere once thought to be
p122
aVunimportant structural elements of the spinal cord
p123
aVthat did nothing more than hold all the important things together,
p124
aVlike the nerves.
p125
aVBut it turns out
p126
aVthe glial cells have a vital role
p127
aVin the modulation, amplification
p128
aVand, in the case of pain, the distortion
p129
aVof sensory experiences.
p130
aVThese glial cells become activated.
p131
aVTheir DNA starts to synthesize new proteins,
p132
aVwhich spill out
p133
aVand interact with adjacent nerves,
p134
aVand they start releasing their neurotransmitters,
p135
aVand those neurotransmitters spill out
p136
aVand activate adjacent glial cells, and so on and so forth,
p137
aVuntil what we have
p138
aVis a positive feedback loop.
p139
aa(lp140
VIt's almost as if somebody came into your home
p141
aVand rewired your walls
p142
aVso that the next time you turned on the light switch,
p143
aVthe toilet flushed three doors down,
p144
aVor your dishwasher went on,
p145
aVor your computer monitor turned off.
p146
aVThat's crazy,
p147
aVbut that's, in fact, what happens
p148
aVwith chronic pain.
p149
aVAnd that's why pain becomes its own disease.
p150
aVThe nervous system has plasticity.
p151
aVIt changes, and it morphs
p152
aVin response to stimuli.
p153
aa(lp154
VWell, what do we do about that?
p155
aVWhat can we do in a case like Chandler's?
p156
aVWe treat these patients in a rather crude fashion
p157
aVat this point in time.
p158
aVWe treat them with symptom-modifying drugs \u2014
p159
aVpainkillers \u2014
p160
aVwhich are, frankly, not very effective
p161
aVfor this kind of pain.
p162
aVWe take nerves that are noisy and active
p163
aVthat should be quiet,
p164
aVand we put them to sleep with local anesthetics.
p165
aVAnd most importantly, what we do
p166
aVis we use a rigorous, and often uncomfortable, process
p167
aVof physical therapy and occupational therapy
p168
aVto retrain the nerves in the nervous system
p169
aVto respond normally
p170
aVto the activities and sensory experiences
p171
aVthat are part of everyday life.
p172
aVAnd we support all of that
p173
aVwith an intensive psychotherapy program
p174
aVto address the despondency, despair and depression
p175
aVthat always accompanies
p176
aVsevere, chronic pain.
p177
aa(lp178
VIt's successful,
p179
aVas you can see from this video of Chandler,
